Sebastian Enrique wrote:

&gt;De un thread the la lista de la GDC de alguien recomendando algunas 
&gt;aplicaciones OpenSource.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;===
&gt;
&gt;There are Open Sources solutions for so many things nowadays. The nice
&gt;thing about Open Source is a lot of times you get cutting edge (and even
&gt;better than very expensive commercial products) products that don&#39;t cost
&gt;you anything and if you choose, you can have a say in or even be a part
&gt;of their future development. Here are programs that I use regularly
&gt;(keep in mind I&#39;m not an artist nor an audio guy) that might be helpful
&gt;in what you&#39;re doing:
&gt;
&gt;OpenOffice (http://www.openoffice.org): Great fully featured office
&gt;package that will also read and write Microsoft office files.
&gt;
&gt;GIMP (http://www.gimp.org): The Gnu Image Manipulation Program is great
&gt;as an alternative to Photoshop and it will read and write Photoshop
&gt;files. They do have an animation module but I haven&#39;t tried it yet.
&gt;
&gt;Audacity (http://audacity.sourceforge.net): This is a great program for
&gt;working with audio files. It&#39;s served all my recording needs.
&gt;
&gt;Miranda Instant Messenger (http://www.miranda-im.org): Nice instant
&gt;messenger that supports AIM, MSN, Yahoo, ICQ, IRC, Jabber, Gadu-Gadu,
&gt;with e-mail notifications for those and Gmail. Not sure if that is of
&gt;use to your kids though.  :)
&gt;
&gt;Well, lots more Open Source that I use (including a bunch for software
&gt;development) and even more that is available. You can check out the site
&gt;for Software Freedom Day and see some links there to things like OpenCD
&gt;which is a whole CD of opensource applications.
&gt;(http://softwarefreedomday.org/index.html)
&gt;
&gt;As for a Java Script tutorial, you can find great tutorials for about
&gt;every language there is through a google search. I&#39;ve learned a few
&gt;languages that way myself. This one looks okay:
&gt;http://www.pageresource.com/jscript/
&gt;
&gt;Hope that helps.
